  "prompt": "What is it like to be a non-Mormon living in Utah?",
  "response": "Living in Utah as a non-Mormon can vary depending on the specific location and community, but here are some common experiences:\n\n1. Cultural differences:\n- Mormon (LDS) culture is prevalent and can feel dominant in many areas\n- Social activities and norms are often influenced by LDS traditions\n- Alcohol, coffee, and tea sales are regulated differently than in other states\n\n2. Professional and social interactions:\n- Many workplaces and social circles have strong Mormon networks\n- Non-Mormons might feel like an \"outsider\" in some professional or community settings\n- Religious discussions can be common and potentially uncomfortable\n\n3. Regional variations:\n- Salt Lake City tends to be more diverse and progressive\n- Rural areas and smaller cities are typically more homogeneous and Mormon-centric\n- Urban areas generally have more religious and cultural diversity\n\n4. Positive aspects:\n- Generally low crime rates\n- Strong sense of community\n- Beautiful natural surroundings\n- Family-friendly environment\n\n5. Potential challenges:\n- Feeling like a minority\n- Limited social opportunities in some areas\n- Potential subtle discrimination\n- Different lifestyle expectations\n\nOverall, experiences vary widely, and many non-Mormons live comfortably and happily in Utah by finding like-minded communities and respecting cultural differences.",
